comment: Change flaky test. The quantize_and_dequantize tests are unfortunately inherently flaky for the value -0.5. After scaling, this value - IN THEORY - equals a quantization interval boundary with well defined rounding behavior. name: A. Unique TensorFlower
comment: Changes in RemoveDuplicatedStrategy(): * Remove strategies when there is any row in resharding_costs with all infinity costs (Adds AllInfinityCosts() for that) * Do not dedup if current strategyvector follows others, so that we can get 1:1 strategy mapping between follower and followee ops, which should make it easier for the ILP solver; * When dedup strategies, in addition to using the output sharding to dedup, also use the input shardings, because multiple input sharding combinations can lead to the same output sharding, and we want to keep all of them because they corresponds to different input strategies.

name: A. Unique TensorFlower

column6: batch_dim == j))```; * Generate replicated strategy for parameters when it does not have any other strategies; * For Broadcast, generate 1D sharding when the mesh is 2D and allow_mixed_mesh_shape is true; * For iota, generate 1D shardings when the mesh is 1D; * Replace ```strategies->following != src_strategies``` with ```i != follow_idx```. \

comment: In large scale distributed training, one Rendezvous instance handles lots of requests in parallel. As a result, the single mutex in Rendezvous cause huge contention which can easily become the bottleneck of performance. This change introduces multiple mutex in Rendezvous to reduce lock contention.

name: Xiao Yu
comment: Two changes to improve TF Executor performance: 1. If there are lots of expensive ops that are ready at the same time, use multiple child threads of dispatch these ready ops. This is because dispatching ops on thread pool can be expensive (e.g. 5000 ops can take 20~100ms depending on the threadpool you are using). 2. When there are lots of ops ready at the same time, avoid recording pending tasks multiple times in TF metrics since adding value in TF metrics can potentially cause lock contention.

comment: #tf-data The `cycle_length` initialization of `ParallelInterleave` currently happens in the Op. This causes the `cycle_length` to have the `MaxParallelism` value of the TPU hosts when the dataset graph is deserialized in tf.data service workers. Move the `cycle_length` initialization to the dataset constructor and serialize the "input cycle length" into the TF graph. This change is guarded by a tf.data experiment: `serialize_input_cycle_length`

name: Jie Sun
comment: python runtime use PyThreadState* to manage python threads. these are saved into a thread-local-storage slot. GIL state have a current PyThreadState* stored in gilstate.tstate_current, indicating who owns GIL now, normally current thread's PyThreadState*. PyEval_SetProfile will set profile function on gilstate.tstate_current, through _PyEval_SetProfile. That's why we need PyThreadState_Swap to change gilstate.tstate_current to each thread's PyThreadState* however _PyEval_SetProfile will assert PyGILState_Check, which check if current thread's PyThreadState* in thread-local-storage is gilstate.tstate_current. because current thread never change, but gilstate.tstate_current are changing at each iteration, this will never works if assert is not compiled out.

comment: Fix segfault by passing cluster-core output association instead of recomputing the association. When there is MPMD model parallelism, TPURewrite creates a program for each core that has a subset of the outputs of the cluster_func's program. So there is an association between cluster outputs and core-program outputs. This association was being computed in different, inconsistent ways which was causing a segfault.

comment: #tf-data This CL has several changes to the stage based autotune: 1) Fix a bug in `ParallelInterleave` total time computation in stage based timing analysis, 2) As a result of the change in 1, increasing parallelism of a `ParallelInterleave` Op may not improve the timing, stop optimization if it is the case, 3) Abandon a stage based optimization iteration if it exceeds the RAM budget because the parameters are likely under-optimized. The other minor change is to simplify the `ParallelInterleave` timing unit tests using parameterized tests.

name: Jie Sun
comment: python runtime use PyThreadState* to manage python threads. these are saved into a thread-local-storage slot. GIL state have a current PyThreadState* stored in gilstate.tstate_current, indicating who owns GIL now, normally current thread's PyThreadState*. PyEval_SetProfile will set profile function on gilstate.tstate_current, through _PyEval_SetProfile. That's why we need PyThreadState_Swap to change gilstate.tstate_current to each thread's PyThreadState* however _PyEval_SetProfile will assert PyGILState_Check, which check if current thread's PyThreadState* in thread-local-storage is gilstate.tstate_current. because current thread never change, but gilstate.tstate_current are changing at each iteration, this will never works if assert is not compiled out.
